                            *Disk, Memory & Performance*
....................................................................................
df -h --Disk Free, shows how much "closet space" is left in GB/MB.

        Goal: Check if the disk is 100% full (which crashes databases).
....................................................................................
du -sh --Disk Usage, find which specific folder is a "space hog."

        Trick: du -sh * | sort -h (Show all folders sorted by size).
....................................................................................
lsblk -- List Block Devices, the "X-ray" for physical hard drives and USBs.

        Goal: See drives even if they aren't "mounted" (active) yet.
....................................................................................
mount -- Attach a physical device (USB/Disk) to a folder so you can use it.

        Example: sudo mount /dev/sdb1 /mnt/myusb
....................................................................................
umount -- Safely detach a device. (Note: No "n" in the middle!)

        Danger: Always umount before unplugging to avoid corrupting data.
....................................................................................
                                *MEMORY & PERFORMANCE*
____________________________________________________________________________________
free -h -- Shows RAM usage. Look at the "Available" column, not "Free."

        Goal: See if your React dev server or Chrome is eating all your memory.
....................................................................................
uptime -- Shows how long the PC has been on and the Load Average.

        Rule: If "Load Average" > Number of CPU Cores, your system is lagging.
....................................................................................
vmstat\ -- Virtual Memory Stat, shows CPU and RAM health every 2 seconds.

        Goal: Check the si/so (Swap) columns; if they are high, you need more RAM.
....................................................................................
iostat(basic) --nput/Output Stat, tells you if your hard drive is too slow.

        Goal: Check %iowait; if high, the CPU is stuck waiting for the disk.
....................................................................................
top -- The "Task Manager" of Linux. Shows every process live.

        Tip: Press q to exit, M to sort by Memory, or P to sort by CPU.
....................................................................................
